    Brugada syndrome is a syndrome of ECG changes associated with clinical features of
  • Associated with atrial fibrillation (Hx of palpitations)
  • Associated with nightmare or thrashing at night.
  • ECG features alone (i.e Brugada sign) is of questionable significance.
  • Brugada syndrome = brugada sign + clinical features.
    • Hx of VF or VT / Syncope / Sudden cardiac death in a family member, Coved type ECGs in family members etc. Source
    • They are precipitated NOT by exercise, but by situations with high vagal tone (sleep, rest), fever and some drugs. (brugadadrugs.org)
  • So far, the only treatment is implantable cardiac defibrillator placement. Quinidine (Class 1 antiarrhmic can be used if ICD is not possible)

⭐CYSTOISOSPORA oocysts are larger than Cyclospora and Cryptosporidium oocysts, are ellipsoidal, and may contain one or two sporoblasts. Multiple (≥ 3) stool specimens may be needed because cyst secretion may be intermittent. Source


4. They infest the epithelial cells of the intestine (intracellular parasites). They produce thick (infective) and thin cysts (autoinfection).
1. ⭐Oocysts are resistant to chlorine levels found in pools.
5. Diagnosis - oocysts in stool but routine stool examination isn't sensitive enough. ⭐Acid fast stains and concentration techniques are required to increase sensitivity.
1. Mnemonic: Crypto - hidden -> hard to find -> need acid fast stain.

  • Cyclospora: Protozoan
  • Obligate human parasite (Humans are only known host)
  • Ingestion of sporulated oocyst from fruits / vegetables / water -> infection -> infection of GI mucosa
  • Low grade fever with anorexia, nausea, flatus, diarrhoea (symptoms can be semi-chronic, lasting several weeks to a month )
  • Non-immunosuppressed patients are at equal risk.
  • Incubation period = 7 days.
  • "symptomatic infections typically manifest as watery diarrhea of varying severity. Other manifestations include complications of dysentery, crampy adbominal paint, further abdominal symptoms, and sometimes non-specific systemic symptoms"
  • Direct faeco oral transmission is not possible as defecated unsporulated oocyst must mature for days / weeks in the environment.
  • Treatment: ⭐trimethoprim sulfamethoxazole.
  • At the milder end of the spectrum, mucosal leishmaniasis (ML) and leishmaniasis recidivans (LR) are caused by oligoparasitic disease associated with a marked cellular immune response.
  • The center of the spectrum consists of localized cutaneous leishmaniasis (LCL), which is the most common clinical presentation.
  • At the opposite end of the spectrum, diffuse cutaneous leishmaniasis (DCL) is caused by polyparasitic disease with a predominance of parasitized macrophages and no granulomatous inflammation.
  • Many species; each one having somewhat different clinical picture.
  • Cutaneous leishmaniasis the commonest form in Sri Lanka. Source
  • lesions are NOT painful.
  • Regional #lymphadenopathy may be present.
  • Satellite nodules can be present.

It begins as a localized lesion that does not ulcerate; rather, amastigotes disseminate to macrophages in other areas of the skin. People who develop DCL usually have a defect in cell mediated immunity.

  • So the causative parasites are L brazilliensis, guyanensis, panamensis, amazonensis)
  • "black fever" refers to the grayish skin colouration that develop probably due to cytokine dysregulation.
  • Incubation period = 2 months;
  • Symptom onset is insidious and patient may feel well despite abnormal clinical findings.
  • #hepatosplenomegaly with #lymphadenopathy (but lymphadenopathy isn't common)
  • Commonest presentation is with ⭐abrupt onset fever with chills and rigors which then continues for weeks.
  • #Splenomegaly seen by the second week followed by #hepatomegaly.
  • Pancytopaenia can lead to thrombocytopenia which causes epistaxis, petechiae, purpura or other bleeding.
  • Untreated, the disease will progress to cause pancytopaenia and immunosuppresion leading to ⭐death in a year by superadded bacterial infection.
  • Complications: DIC or macrophage activation syndrome.
  • Diagnosis: Identification of the organisms in aspirate of bone marrow or liver or spleen.
    • sensitivities: spleen (90%) -> Bone marrow -> lymph nodes.
    • Also montenigro test (similar to mantoux test for TB) - but this test is negative in the active phase of the disease. It also remains positive for life so in endemic areas, 70% are positive.

Post-kala-azar dermal leishmaniasis (PKDL) is a complication of visceral leishmaniasis (VL); it is characterised by a macular, maculopapular, and nodular rash in a patient who has recovered from VL and who is otherwise well.

  • Median time to onset is about 6 months to 2 years after treatment.
  • Associated with Leishmania donovani.
  • Ticks are not involved in typhus.

[!INFO] Treatment of MODY
Mnemonic: mutations with 'a' don't need insulin, mutations with 'b' definitely need insulin.

  • acceleration of terminal repolarization (causes T wave abnormalities)
  • Depression of conduction between adjacent myocytes -> Prolongation of PR and QRS duration. Source
    | Level | Changes | Basis |
    | --------- | --------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
    | 5.5 - 6.5 | Tall t waves | Repolarization abnormalities |
    | 6.5 - 7 | P wave widening and flattening, broadening of PR interval | Progressive atrial paralysis |
    | 7.0 - 9.0 | Sinus brady, AV block, AF, conduction blocks | Conduction abnormalities |
    | > 9.0 | Sine wave | Peri arrest |
    In hyperkalemia, ECG changes progress from peaked T-waves to widened QRS and eventually to ventricular tachycardia, fibrillation or pulseless electrical activity arrest.  These progressive changes can correlate with rising potassium levels.

[!INFO] STU

T wave diminished
U wave increased
The U-wave is a deflection following the T wave. Potassium levels that are critically low (<1.7 mmol/L) can lead to ⭐torsades de pointes or “twisting of the points”, a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia.

Effect of pregnancy on pharmacokinetics

#pregnancy
Source

  • Maternal plasma albumin is reduced -> lower protein binding of drugs.
  • Increased renal elimination due to increased GFR but renal reabosorption may increase for some drugs.
  • Slow gastric emptying and increased gastric pH reduce absorption.
  • Slower intestinal transit time increases absorption.
    • Net effect: for most drugs absorption is unchanged.
  • Lipophillic drugs cross the placenta readily.
  • The placenta prevents passage of drugs like enoxaparin
    • Progesterone induces liver enzymes.
    • Hepatobiliary clearance is reduced due to the cholestatic effects of oestrogen.
      see [[Hypertension in pregnancy#Other physiological changes in pregnancy]]

There are chemical and non chemical stimuli for regulation of respiration.
The sensors in the system are central and peripheral chemoreceptors. They are sensitive to different parameters.
Since wider inspired PO2s can be tolerated by the body, the main regulators of respiratory drive in most states are PCO2 and pH.
⭐

  • Overall, PCO2 exerts the most influence on respiratory control.
    PO2 based resiratory drive overrides the above two factors when PO2 drops to 'dangerously' low levels (i.e PaO2 approx 60.)
  • Even Lower PO2 levels will directly inhibit the respiratory center.

Above Pao2 of 80 mm Hg, O2 has little effect on respiratory drive
